      "side": 1,
      "message": "Framing: the proposal characterizes local-module.cue throughout as \"development-time configuration\" (here, and lines 113/120/126/472, plus \"local development\" on line 12), but that conflates two orthogonal properties:\n\n- Scope — replace is honored only in the main module and never propagates to downstream consumers (lines 86, 165). This is the property the design actually enforces.\n- Lifecycle — \"development-time\", i.e. ephemeral/personal/machine-specific. This is what the name and the headline prose imply.\n\nThe proposal\u0027s own content contradicts the lifecycle framing: UC2 is \"committed on purpose\", UC3/UC4 are \"useful to share across a team\", and \"Why not .gitignore\" states \"Committing the replace is the correct behaviour there\". So replaces are frequently committed, shared and persistent — not development-time. The defining guarantee is scope (main-module-only, non-propagating); development-time replacement is just the most common use of that capability, not its essence.\n\nSuggest reframing to lead with the scope property — \"configuration that changes how you build without changing what your consumers see\" — and demote \"development-time\" to \"the common case\". The name local-module.cue reinforces the narrower reading (it works if \"local\" means \"local to this module / not propagated\", but the surrounding \"local development\" / \"machine-specific\" language reads it as machine-local), so it\u0027s worth at least making the prose consistent about which sense is meant.",
      "revId": "de69d66dbcc57a8073041d01eca42146c1c410f6",
      "serverId": "d5d70762-12d0-45a1-890d-524b12d3f735"
    },
