      "writtenOn": "2026-06-12T10:20:49Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The parenthetical (\"this should not happen unless someone is publishing modules without using `cue mod publish`\") understates why client-side rejection is necessary, framing it as an accident only. The reason the check has to live in the consuming client — rather than relying on the publish-side guarantees described under \"Interaction with registries\" — is that those guarantees don\u0027t bind the threat: the Central Registry\u0027s rejection covers only the Central Registry; `cue mod publish`\u0027s strip covers only modules published via our CLI; an arbitrary OCI registry or a direct push is covered by neither, and a local-module.cue\u0027s replace directives (directory replaces pointing at arbitrary local paths, or module-version replaces redirecting deps) make a malicious artifact a real concern, not just a sloppy one.\n\nSuggest strengthening to make explicit that rejection defends against accidental *and* malicious artifacts from any registry, which is precisely why it must be enforced on download in the client. (Note: as of now this is not yet enforced — the consume-path zip check has no local-module.cue branch — so the proposal is specifying intended behaviour here.)",
      "revId": "de69d66dbcc57a8073041d01eca42146c1c410f6",
      "serverId": "d5d70762-12d0-45a1-890d-524b12d3f735"
    },
